Well, today I'm flying this plane.
The first complaint: We need a cute flight logbook. Black is too boring, and what's supposed to be pink is actually salmon red.
I've always wanted to fly.
Today my dream came true... I flew this plane today. I still can't believe it.
FlightAware's data.
On Saturday, I plan to give it another try. The weather doesn't look good now, but it's only Monday.
It seems the challenges in this area have already begun to show. Due to the FAA's stance on certain drugs, I may find it difficult to obtain my medical certificate.
This is not impossible, but it would require a significant amount of time and a lot of extra work.
Although this is somewhat discouraging, it merely adds another problem to be solved, and currently seems "indeed" solvable, just requiring a significant amount of time and money.
If you want to know what challenges I am about to face:
The FAA does not approve of ADHD medications. If you are taking medication for ADHD, you definitely won't get your medical certificate.
https://youtu.be/W5JSfq6LLAU?si=xIxPaY8ayqqNSj4c
If I have the opportunity to customize the tail number of the aircraft in the future, it must be some variant of N1337_, where _ represents any available letter character.
Of course, the sun will surely rise tomorrow even without me, ha ha. What a letdown.
I need to fly again. But this damn weather is really not cooperating.
Welcome to the world of general aviation! 😜
Based on the ads on YouTube that I should see, the videos recommended to me, and the comments, I feel that airlines tend to lean towards conservative tracking.
If the weather permits, I'll fly again on Saturday.
Additionally, I found a pink flight log.
Saturday morning. I did this today ^_^
#TeaganAir
The flight log book is now officially in use. I have 2.3 hours of flight records ^_^
#TeaganAir
If you asked me to describe what it feels like to fly a small plane, I'd say it's like riding a motorcycle/at-sv/ATV and a boat combined, at 4000 feet in the air.
On the ground, situations change rapidly. There is a certain level of instability, so a motorcycle/ATV is needed.
Additionally, you might not know that when driving the plane on the ground, you control the direction with your feet, not with a joystick. It uses rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
While flying in the air, you will feel颠簸和摇晃like being on a boat on water. Although you can control the plane, sometimes the airflow can make you a bit disoriented, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just like sailors adapt to sailing.
There's also a random fun fact about this:
Flying is quite physically demanding. Today, my back and legs are sore to the point where it feels like I've been to the gym.
This isn't as simple as going for a drive on a Sunday. To me, a novice, it feels more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, Happy Saturday. Welcome to 4000 feet in the air.
I will fly again tomorrow, and we will practice stall and slow flight.
Today's weather wasn't very stable but super fun. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed dropped to 16 miles per hour, while our airspeed was still 65 miles per hour.
Today the weather is sunny, though there's a bit of fog at high altitude, the visibility is still great.
